<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-317-240  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 317 240.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  March 15 1990 v16 n6 p38(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Users responding to Computer Talk's voice system. (Computer TalkTechnology Inc.'s Talking Computer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Frangini, Monica.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Computer Talk Inc is adopting standard telephone technology intoan easily accessible database technology enabling ordinarytelephone users to hook up with large computers with sophisticateddata bases.andP;  The Talking Computer relies on an interactive voiceresponse technology based on the CTalk communications softwarerunning on an IBM PS/2 microcomputer.andP;  Chief uses of the serviceare for banking, stock trading and shopping.andP;  Customers of TorontoDominion Bank, for example, can perform bill payment, fundtransfer and account balancing functions by simply pressingnumbers on a Touch-Tone keypad.andP;  Beginning three years ago,Computer Talk has grown into a company with 400 installed linescoast-to-coast and a workforce of 25.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Computer Talk Inc. (products).andO;Product:   The Talking Computer (Microcomputer) (usage)IBM PS/2 (Microcomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Information Storage and RetrievalCommunications TechnologyInteractive SystemsVoice CommunicationsData BasesCommunications SoftwareBankingCommunications Service Suppliers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>RICHMOND HILL, Ont.andP;  -- Computer Talk Technology Inc. (CTT) is givingordinary people access to sophisticated technology by turning the telephoneinto a computer terminal, said its founder Mandle Cheung last month at theopening of CTT's new headquarters here.andM;&quot;All of a sudden with a telephone you can access multimillion-dollarcomputers with very sophisticated databases doing your banking, shopping andstock trading,&quot; said Cheung.andP;  &quot;Everyone has access to a telephone, everyoneknows how to use it and there's no training required.&quot;andM;The Talking Computer sits between a company's host computer and anytelephone, transforming it into a terminal.andP;  It is an interactive voiceresponse (IVR) system based on IBM PS/2 computers and the proprietary CTalkapplication software.andM;Banking, for example, can be done at home through the use of Bankline, whichis a new service for Toronto Dominion Bank customers in the London, Ont.andO;area, explained Cheung.andP;  Following voice prompts from CTT's Talking Computer,customers are instructed to press numbers on a Touch-Tone keypad.andP;  Routine,cashless transactions such as bill payment, account balance information andtransfer of funds are all available.andM;Cheung said the company hopes to maintain its leadership in the IVR marketcompeting against giants such as ATandamp;T.andP;  &quot;We're into the U.S.andP;  now and we hopeto expand to Europe and the Pacific Rim,&quot; he said.andM;Beginning as a basement operation three years ago, CTT now has more than 400telephone lines installed coast to coast.andP;  The company's staff has grown fromone to 25.andM;&quot;This is an example of the type of company that is so important to the futureof this province,&quot; said Doug Carrothers, parliamentary assistant to theminister of trade and technology Monte Kwinter.andM;Carrothers, who attended the opening of CTT's head office, said he was veryimpressed with CTT technology.andP;  &quot;Canada's investment in computer-assisteddesign and manufacturing has been behind other countries,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;We'recatching up to the rest of our competitors with the help of companies such asCTT,&quot; he told Cheung prior to the ribbon-cutting ceremony.andM;Richmond Hill Mayor William Bell was also in attendance.andP;  He said he was&quot;seriously considering&quot; applying CTT technology to his offices.andP;  &quot;Thetechnology is marvelous and exciting and we're so happy that you've come toRichmond Hill,&quot; he said.andM;Among the demonstrations available at the new CTT facility was a faxinterface feature which allows customers access to a company's fax machine,through a main phone number to obtain hardcopies of desired information.andM;For example, a credit bureau can fax a detailed credit history at thecustomer's request.andP;  Banks on the other hand might release an interim accountstatement, as part of a home banking system.andM;Other demonstrations included the voice recognition system which allows usersof rotary phones to say numbers to make a menu selection or enter data.andM;The speech recognition module is an option that can be added to any TalkingComputer system.andO;</TEXT></DOC>